\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As Saulson and GonzÃ¡lez neatly described 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saulson1990thermal,Gonz\\'alez199512,1995PhDT........16G"

\end_inset

, all mechanical oscillators have intrinsic thermal noise.
 Through the fluctuation-dissipation theorem, any lossy oscillator at finite
 temperature drives itself with thermal fluctuations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A torsion balance suspended in sufficiently high vacuum is 'internally damped'.
 This is described by adding an imaginary part to the torsion fiber's spring
 constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\rightarrow\kappa(1+i\phi)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\frac{1}{Q}$
\end_inset

 is the 'loss angle' of the fiber.
 In torque units, thermal noise is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau^{2}(f)=4k_{B}T\frac{\kappa}{2\pi fQ}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
